{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28b78a061ffeNWRR7H8K4xvvu2","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d74877419001SagwdASsd5cNNj","parts":[{"id":"prt_d74877c6d001OfmVoQ5P5Gll62","messageID":"msg_d74877419001SagwdASsd5cNNj","sessionID":"ses_28b78a061ffeNWRR7H8K4xvvu2","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_217c5ccab49c43c195da15f8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/amperser/proselint/main/logo.png\" alt=\"proselint logo\" width=\"200\">\n2: \n3: ![Workflow status](https://github.com/amperser/proselint/actions/workflows/ci-lint-test.yml/badge.svg)\n4: [![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/amperser/proselint/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=8E0I9sRpot)](https://codecov.io/gh/amperser/proselint)\n5: [![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-BSD-blue.svg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BSD_licenses)\n6: \n7: Writing is notoriously hard, even for the best writers, and it's not for lack of\n8: good advice — a tremendous amount of knowledge about the craft is strewn across\n9: usage guides, dictionaries, technical manuals, essays, pamphlets, websites, and\n10: the hearts and minds of great authors and editors. But poring over Strunk &\n11: White hardly makes one a better writer — it turns you into neither Strunk nor\n12: White. And nobody has the capacity to apply all the advice from *Garner’s Modern\n13: English Usage*, an 1100-page usage guide, to everything they write. In fact, the\n14: whole notion that one becomes a better writer by reading advice on writing rests\n15: on untenable assumptions about learning and memory. The traditional formats of\n16: knowledge about writing are thus essentially inert, waiting to be transformed.\n17: \n18: We devised a simple solution: `proselint`, a linter for English prose. A linter\n19: is a computer program that, akin to a spell checker, scans through a file and\n20: detects issues — like how a real lint roller helps you get unwanted lint off of\n21: your shirt.\n22: \n23: `proselint` places the world's greatest writers and editors by your side, where\n24: they whisper suggestions on how to improve your prose. You’ll be guided by\n25: advice inspired by Bryan Garner, David Foster Wallace, Chuck Palahniuk, Steve\n26: Pinker, Mary Norris, Mark Twain, Elmore Leonard, George Orwell, Matthew\n27: Butterick, William Strunk, Elwyn White, Philip Corbett, Ernest Gowers, and the\n28: editorial staff of the world’s finest literary magazines and newspapers, among\n29: others. Our goal is to aggregate knowledge about best practices in writing and\n30: to make that knowledge immediately accessible to all authors in the form of a\n31: linter for prose; all in a neat command-line utility that you can integrate into\n32: other tools, scripts, and workflows.\n33: \n34: ## Installation\n35: \n36: To get this up and running, install it using [pip].\n37: \n38: ```bash\n39: pip install proselint\n40: ```\n41: \n42: [pip]: https://packaging.python.org/installing/#use-pip-for-installing\n43: \n44: ### Fedora\n45: \n46: ```bash\n47: sudo dnf install proselint\n48: ```\n49: \n50: ### Debian\n51: \n52: ```bash\n53: sudo apt install python3-proselint\n54: ```\n55: \n56: ### Ubuntu\n57: \n58: ```bash\n59: sudo add-apt-repository universe\n60: sudo apt install python3-proselint\n61: ```\n62: \n63: ### Nix\n64: \n65: `proselint` is packaged by [`nixpkgs`].\n66: \n67: ### pre-commit\n68: \n69: To use proselint with [pre-commit](https://pre-commit.com/) (by [Andy Airey](https://github.com/aairey)), point its config at this repository:\n70: \n71: ```yaml\n72: repos:\n73:   - repo: https://github.com/amperser/proselint\n74:     rev: v0.16.0\n75:     hooks:\n76:       - id: proselint\n77: ```\n78: \n79: Be sure to change `rev` to use the desired `proselint` git tag or revision.\n80: \n81: \n82: #### Declarative\n83: \n84: ```nix\n85: environment.systemPackages = [pkgs.proselint];\n86: ```\n87: \n88: #### Imperative\n89: \n90: ```bash\n91: nix profile install nixpkgs#proselint\n92: ```\n93: \n94: [`nixpkgs`]: https://search.nixos.org/packages?channel=25.05&show=proselint\n95: \n96: ### Plugins for other software\n97: \n98: `proselint` is available on:\n99: \n100: - A [demo editor](http://proselint.com/write)\n101: - Emacs via [Flycheck](http://www.flycheck.org/) or via [Flymake](https://sr.ht/~manuel-uberti/flymake-proselint/)\n102: - Vim via [ALE](https://github.com/w0rp/ale) or [Syntastic](https://github.com/vim-syntastic/syntastic) (thanks to @lcd047, @Carreau, and [Daniel M. Capella](https://github.com/polyzen))\n103: - Neovim via [none-ls.nvim](https://github.com/nvimtools/none-ls.nvim) (none-ls has [diagnostics](https://github.com/nvimtools/none-ls.nvim/blob/main/doc/BUILTINS.md#proselint-1) and [code actions](https://github.com/nvimtools/none-ls.nvim/blob/main/doc/BUILTINS.md#proselint) for proselint)\n104: - [MegaLinter](https://oxsecurity.github.io/megalinter/latest/descriptors/spell_proselint/)\n105: \n106: The following plugins are also available, but they are archived or unmaintained:\n107: \n108: - [Atom Editor](https://github.com/smockle/linter-proselint) (thanks to [Clay Miller](https://github.com/smockle)).\n109: - [coala](https://github.com/coala/bear-docs/blob/master/docs/ProseLintBear.rst) (thanks to the [coala Development Group](https://github.com/coala-analyzer))\n110: - [Danger](https://github.com/dbgrandi/danger-prose) (thanks to [David Grandinetti](https://github.com/dbgrandi) and [Orta Therox](https://github.com/orta))\n111: - [IntelliJ](https://github.com/kropp/intellij-proselint) (by [Victor Kropp](https://github.com/kropp))\n112: - Neovim via [null-ls](https://github.com/jose-elias-alvarez/null-ls.nvim) (null-ls has [diagnostics](https://github.com/jose-elias-alvarez/null-ls.nvim/blob/main/lua/null-ls/builtins/diagnostics/proselint.lua) and [code actions](https://github.com/jose-elias-alvarez/null-ls.nvim/blob/main/lua/null-ls/builtins/code_actions/proselint.lua) for proselint)\n113: - [Phabricator's `arc` CLI](https://github.com/google/arc-proselint) (thanks to [Jeff Verkoeyen](https://github.com/jverkoey))\n114: - [Sublime Text](https://github.com/amperser/proselint/tree/main/plugins/sublime/SublimeLinter-contrib-proselint)\n115: - [Visual Studio Code](https://github.com/ppeszko/vscode-proselint) (thanks to [Patryk Peszko](https://github.com/ppeszko))\n116: \n117: ### Usage\n118: \n119: Suppose you have a document `text.md` with the following text:\n120: \n121: ```md\n122: John is very unique.\n123: ```\n124: \n125: You can run `proselint` over the document using the command line:\n126: \n127: ```bash\n128: proselint check text.md\n129: ```\n130: \n131: This prints a list of suggestions to stdout, one per line. Each suggestion is of\n132: the form:\n133: \n134: ```bash\n135: file:<line>:<column>: <check_name>: <message>\n136: ```\n137: \n138: For example,\n139: \n140: ```bash\n141: text.md:1:9: uncomparables: Comparison of an uncomparable: 'very unique' is not comparable.\n142: ```\n143: \n144: The command-line utility can also print suggestions in JSON using the\n145: `--output-format json` option. In this case, the output is considerably richer,\n146: following our [stable wire schema].\n147: \n148: ```jsonc\n149: {\n150:   \"result\": {\n151:     \"file:///path/to/text.md\": {\n152:       \"diagnostics\": [\n153:         {\n154:           // Name of the check that output this suggestion.\n155:           \"check_path\": \"uncomparables\",\n156:           // Message to describe the suggestion\n157:           \"message\": \"Comparison of an uncomparable: 'very unique' is not comparable.\",\n158:           // Line and column where the error begins in the source\n159:           \"pos\": [1, 9],\n160:           // Absolute start and end of the error in the source\n161:           \"span\": [9, 20],\n162:           // Suggested replacements for the content, if applicable\n163:           \"replacements\": null,\n164:         }\n165:       ]\n166:     }\n167:   }\n168: }\n169: ```\n170: \n171: To run the linter as part of another Python program, you can use the `LintFile`\n172: class in `proselint.tools`. This requires `CheckRegistry` to be populated.\n173: \n174: ```python\n175: from proselint.checks import __register__\n176: from proselint.registry import CheckRegistry\n177: from proselint.tools import LintFile\n178: \n179: CheckRegistry().register_many(__register__)\n180: suggestions = LintFile(\"source-name\", \"This sentence is very unique\").lint()\n181: ```\n182: \n183: This will return a list of suggestions:\n184: \n185: ```python\n186: [LintResult(\n187:     check_result=CheckResult(\n188:         check_path='uncomparables',\n189:         message=\"Comparison of an uncomparable: 'very unique' is not comparable.\",\n190:         span=(18, 29),\n191:         replacements=None,\n192:     ),\n193:     pos=(1, 18),\n194: )]\n195: ```\n196: \n197: [stable wire schema]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/blob/main/docs/wire-schema.md\n198: \n199: ### Checks\n200: \n201: You can disable any of the checks by modifying\n202: `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/proselint/config.json`. If `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME` is not set or\n203: empty, `~/.config/proselint/config.json` will be used. Check selection is\n204: granular at any level, illustrated in the following example:\n205: \n206: ```json\n207: {\n208:   \"checks\": {\n209:     \"typography\": true,\n210:     \"typography.symbols\": false,\n211:     \"typography.symbols.curly_quotes\": true,\n212:     \"typography.punctuation.hyperbole\": false,\n213:   }\n214: }\n215: ```\n216: \n217: This configuration would enable all checks in the `typography` module, excluding\n218: `typography.punctuation.hyperbole` and those in `typography.symbols`, but\n219: preserving `typography.symbols.curly_quotes`. Using this system allows you to\n220: concisely and precisely select checks at an individual level.\n221: \n222: | ID    | Description     |\n223: | ----- | --------------- |\n224: | `annotations` | Catch annotations left in the text |\n225: | `archaism` | Avoid archaic forms |\n226: | `cliches.hell` | Avoid a common cliché regarding hell |\n227: | `cliches.misc` | Avoid clichés |\n228: | `dates_times.am_pm` | Format the time of day correctly |\n229: | `dates_times.dates` | Format dates appropriately |\n230: | `hedging` | Avoid undermining yourself with uncertainty |\n231: | `industrial_language.airlinese` | Avoid jargon of the airline industry |\n232: | `industrial_language.bureaucratese` | Avoid bureaucratese |\n233: | `industrial_language.chatspeak` | Avoid lolling and other chatspeak |\n234: | `industrial_language.commercialese` | Avoid jargon of the commercial world |\n235: | `industrial_language.corporate_speak` | Avoid corporate buzzwords |\n236: | `industrial_language.jargon` | Avoid miscellaneous jargon |\n237: | `lexical_illusions` | Avoid repeating words or phrases |\n238: | `malapropisms` | Avoid common malapropisms |\n239: | `misc.apologizing` | Be confident and avoid excessive apologizing |\n240: | `misc.back_formations` | Avoid redundant backformations |\n241: | `misc.but` | Do not start a paragraph with \"But...\" |\n242: | `misc.capitalization` | Capitalize only what ought to be capitalized |\n243: | `misc.composition` | Adhere to principles of composition |\n244: | `misc.currency` | Avoid redundant currency symbols |\n245: | `misc.debased` | Avoid debased language |\n246: | `misc.false_plurals` | Avoid false plurals |\n247: | `misc.greylist` | Avoid greylisted terms |\n248: | `misc.illogic` | Avoid illogical forms |\n249: | `misc.inferior_superior` | Superior to, not than |\n250: | `misc.institution_name` | Use the correct names of institutions |\n251: | `misc.latin` | Avoid overuse of Latin phrases |\n252: | `misc.many_a` | Use singular forms with \"many a\" |\n253: | `misc.metadiscourse` | Avoid discussing the discussion |\n254: | `misc.narcissism` | Talk about the subject, not its study |\n255: | `misc.not_guilty` | Avoid \"not guilty beyond a reasonable doubt\" |\n256: | `misc.phrasal_adjectives` | Hyphenate phrasal adjectives correctly |\n257: | `misc.preferred_forms` | Use the preferred forms of terms |\n258: | `misc.pretension` | Do not be pretentious |\n259: | `misc.professions` | Use the right names for jobs |\n260: | `misc.scare_quotes` | Do not misuse scare quotes |\n261: | `misc.suddenly` | Retain suddenness by not using \"suddenly\" |\n262: | `misc.tense_present` | Follow advice from Tense Present |\n263: | `misc.waxed` | Use adjectives for waxed, as in \"wax poetic\" |\n264: | `misc.whence` | Avoid redundancy with \"whence\" |\n265: | `mixed_metaphors` | Do not mix metaphors |\n266: | `mondegreens` | Avoid mondegreens |\n267: | `needless_variants` | Use preferred forms over uncommon variants |\n268: | `nonwords` | Do not use nonwords |\n269: | `oxymorons` | Avoid oxymorons |\n270: | `psychology` | Avoid misusing psychological terms |\n271: | `redundancy.misc` | Avoid redundancy in phrases |\n272: | `redundancy.ras_syndrome` | Avoid redundancy in acronyms |\n273: | `restricted.elementary` | Restrict writing to terms from elementary school |\n274: | `restricted.top1000` | Restrict writing to the top 1000 words by usage |\n275: | `skunked_terms` | Avoid using skunked terms |\n276: | `social_awareness.lgbtq` | Be aware of LGBTQ+ terminology |\n277: | `social_awareness.nword` | Take responsibility for use of \"the n-word\" |\n278: | `social_awareness.sexism` | Be aware of sexist language |\n279: | `spelling.able_atable` | Use the correct form of -able and -atable |\n280: | `spelling.able_ible` | Use the correct form of -able and -ible |\n281: | `spelling.ally_ly` | Use the correct form of -ally and -ly |\n282: | `spelling.ance_ence` | Use the correect form of -ance and -ence |\n283: | `spelling.athletes` | Spell the names of athletes correctly |\n284: | `spelling.consistency` | Be consistent in spelling |\n285: | `spelling.ely_ly` | Use the correct form of -ely and -ly |\n286: | `spelling.em_im_en_in` | Use the correct form of -em, -im, -en, and -in |\n287: | `spelling.er_or` | Use the correct form of -er and -or |\n288: | `spelling.in_un` | Use the correct form of -in and -un |\n289: | `spelling.misc` | Spell miscellaneous terms correctly |\n290: | `spelling.ve_of` | Use the correct form of -ve and -of |\n291: | `terms.animal_adjectives` | Use the right adjectives for likening animals |\n292: | `terms.denizen_labels` | Use the right names for denizens |\n293: | `terms.eponymous_adjectives` | Use the right names for likening people |\n294: | `terms.venery` | Use the right names for groups of animals |\n295: | `typography.diacritical_marks` | Use diacritical marks |\n296: | `typography.punctuation` | Use punctuation correctly |\n297: | `typography.symbols` | Use symbols correctly |\n298: | `uncomparables` | Do not compare uncomparables |\n299: | `weasel_words` | Avoid weasel words |\n300: \n301: ### Contributing\n302: \n303: Interested in contributing to `proselint`? Great — there are plenty of ways you\n304: can help. Check out our [contributing guidelines], where we describe how you\n305: can help us build `proselint` into the greatest writing tool in the world.\n306: \n307: - [Issue Tracker](http://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues)\n308: - [Source Code](http://github.com/amperser/proselint)\n309: \n310: [contributing guidelines]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md\n311: \n312: ### Support\n313: \n314: If you run into a problem, please [open an issue](http://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues).\n315: \n316: ### Running Tests\n317: \n318: Automated tests are included in the `tests` directory. To run these\n319: tests locally, you can use `pytest` via `poe test`.\n320: \n321: ### License\n322: \n323: The project is licensed under the [BSD license](LICENSE.md).\n\n(End of file - total 323 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"<img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/amperser/proselint/main/logo.png\" alt=\"proselint logo\" width=\"200\">\n\n![Workflow status](https://github.com/amperser/proselint/actions/workflows/ci-lint-test.yml/badge.svg)\n[![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/amperser/proselint/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=8E0I9sRpot)](https://codecov.io/gh/amperser/proselint)\n[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-BSD-blue.svg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BSD_licenses)\n\nWriting is notoriously hard, even for the best writers, and it's not for lack of\ngood advice — a tremendous amount of knowledge about the craft is strewn across\nusage guides, dictionaries, technical manuals, essays, pamphlets, websites, and\nthe hearts and minds of great authors and editors. But poring over Strunk &\nWhite hardly makes one a better writer — it turns you into neither Strunk nor\nWhite. And nobody has the capacity to apply all the advice from *Garner’s Modern\nEnglish Usage*, an 1100-page usage guide, to everything they write. In fact, the\nwhole notion that one becomes a better writer by reading advice on writing rests\non untenable assumptions about learning and memory. The traditional formats of\nknowledge about writing are thus essentially inert, waiting to be transformed.\n\nWe devised a simple solution: `proselint`, a linter for English prose. A linter\nis a computer program that, akin to a spell checker, scans through a file and\ndetects issues — like how a real lint roller helps you get unwanted lint off of","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.md","time":{"start":1775776529791,"end":1775776529802}}}]}
